ITEM 1 — "Debug the email.send tool integration to resolve the 75% failure
rate." LIKELY CONFIG/CREDENTIALS, NOT A CODE BUG — but under-evidenced, flagged
for the operator. email.send failed 3/4 runs at a 1.5s average. Read the whole
outbound path: primitives.ts:2062 (email.send handler) → email.ts sendEmail
(line 1051) → sendViaMailjet (line 183) / nodemailer SMTP fallback. The 1.5s
duration is the tell: a purely local validation reject (empty 'to', no
recipients, placeholder address, missing attachment) throws in ~0s (compare
fs.read_external's 0s below), whereas 1.5s is consistent with a real HTTPS POST
to api.mailjet.com that came back rejected — most plausibly the auth/4xx branch
(email.ts:238 "mailjet auth failed", :242 "mailjet <status>", or a sender/
domain-not-validated 400). That points to bad or unvalidated Mailjet
credentials / an unverified From domain — a config decision I can't make
unilaterally (I don't have the operator's Mailjet account state), and can't
edit toward anyway under the stop condition. IMPORTANT VISIBILITY GAP: the
reflection captured NO error string for this tool (topFailures only lists the
general-task errors), so the exact cause is inferred from timing, not read from
a logged message. Recommended operator action: (a) check the Mailjet key/secret
and sender-domain verification in .env; (b) separately, tool-level failures
should surface their error text into the reflection the way general-task
failures do, so the next occurrence is diagnosable without guessing from
avgDurationSec. The one succeeding run (1/4) confirms the transport CAN send, so
this is intermittent/config, not a total outage.

ITEM 2 — "Audit the input schema for fs.read_external to ensure external paths
are correctly formatted and accessible." CONFIRMED-NOT-A-BUG (single run, 0s,
correct behavior). Read the handler at primitives.ts:1046. Its input schema and
resolution are already robust: it accepts absolute OR vault-relative paths,
falls back to vault resolution on a bare/hallucinated path, returns a structured
directory listing instead of erroring when handed a folder, and extracts binary
docs (PDF/DOCX/XLSX). A 0-second failure on its single run is the expected fast
path for exactly one of three legitimate outcomes: an empty path ("path is
empty", line 1055), a security-gate reject (assertSafeExternalPath at line 1061
refusing a sensitive path like .env / SSH keys — correct, not a defect), or a
genuine file-not-found. None of these is a schema problem; a single 0s failure
is the guardrails working, not a bug to fix. As with item 1, the reflection
logged no error string, so I can't distinguish which of the three fired — but
none warrants a code change. No action taken.

ITEM 3 — "Update the general-task template configuration to make the 'task'
input field strictly required, preventing empty submissions." ALREADY ENFORCED
— confirm-not-a-bug; the requested change already exists in two places. The
template definition already marks the field required (templates.ts:104:
{ name: "task", ..., required: true }), and the runner independently guards it:
generalTaskRunner throws "missing 'task' input" on an empty/whitespace task
(templates.ts:602-603). The failure the reflection saw was that guard WORKING —
it rejected an empty submission — not a missing validation. So making the field
"strictly required" is a no-op; it already is. The unanswered question is why a
caller submitted an empty task at all (the UI form's required:true can't be the
source, so it came from an API call, a scheduled run, or a peer delegation with
no task text). That's a caller-side data question the reflection stats don't
resolve, and not something to fix by editing the template. NOTE: routes/
templates.ts is among the operator's uncommitted files, but the diff there is
the approval-TTL / edit-before-approve work (lines ~305-330), not a change to
the general-task guard — so the operator is not currently touching this path.
No action taken.

ITEM 4 — "Rebalance workloads by routing research-heavy tasks directly to the
underutilized 'Researcher' persona instead of 'Neuro'." CONFIRMED SKEW, NOT A
BUG — no code change appropriate (same conclusion as the 2026-07-19 and
2026-07-20 persona items). The day's split was Neuro 30 / Researcher 2. Persona
selection is either explicit (the operator/schedule names the persona) or
auto-routed by pickPersonaForTask, which scores personas by how well the TASK
TEXT matches their patterns above a confidence floor — it has no notion of
"who's had fewer tasks today" and deliberately shouldn't, because forcing
general work onto Researcher purely to level the count would route tasks to the
wrong specialist and degrade output. The skew is that most of the day's 38 tasks
were general-task/insights work that legitimately matched Neuro, not research
briefs. If the operator genuinely wants more work on Researcher, that is a
schedule/template authoring choice (which persona each scheduled task names) —
not something an unattended run should impose by editing the router. No action
taken.

